<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-10-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-10-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="819" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d819">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Terrell</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-10-23"><hi rend="italic">October 23,
                                    1896.</hi></date></dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1160.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            No. 1014 of the 9th instant, inclosing an extract from a dispatch from
                            Consul Jewett, at Sivas, to Consul-General Short, in which he says the
                            continuance of guards for Americans in the interior of Turkey is
                            necessary.</p>
                        <p>The Department agrees with you in the necessity for protecting our
                            citizens in Turkey, and demands for adequate guards for Americans and
                            their property should not be relaxed.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Richard Olney.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>